		<tr valign=top>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				Hehe, &quot;veteran&quot;... ? <br>  <br> first game I played on the pc was Wolfenstein 3d (shareware)... that must have been around 1993 or so... about 10 years ago.  <br>  <br> there, the mouse was never used.  <br>  <br> arrow key up = move forwards <br> arrow key down = move backwards <br> arrow key left = turn left <br> arrow key right = turn right <br>  <br> ctrl = shoot <br> alt = strafe <br> space = open <br> number keys = weapons <br>  <br> that was it.  <br>  <br> from then, I played doom, doom2, blake stone (shareware), rise of the triad, duke nukem forever, quake (and there after pretty much all the popular fps and a lot of the unpopular ones).  <br>  <br> it was only when I got to quake that I started using the mouse at all. but I was used to the &quot;turn&quot; keys from several years of training. and it was in quake multiplayer that I realised that I needed the move left and more right keys as well. <br>  <br> so the compromise was to move the position of my left hand slightly, from the arrow keys to the numeric key pad, keep the move / turn keys patten and add the move right / move left keys above the turn keys... <br>  <br> this way, I can circle strafe with just two keys (ie, move right + turn left) and use the mouse for fine tuning the aim...		

			</td>
		</tr>
